    <!-- FAQ Content -->
      <section class="faq-content" aria-labelledby="faq-section">
        <div class="container">
            <div class="faq-grid">
                <div class="faq-list" id="faq-list" aria-live="polite">

                    <!-- Item 1 -->
                    <div class="faq-item" data-keywords="battery drain power settings background apps age capacity">
                        <div class="faq-question" role="button" aria-expanded="false" tabindex="0">
                            <div class="q-main">
                                <div class="q-text">Why is my laptop battery draining so fast?</div>
                                <div class="q-meta">Common causes & quick checks</div>
                                <div class="faq-tags" aria-hidden="true">
                                    <span class="faq-tag">Difficulty: Easy</span>
                                    <span class="faq-tag">Time: 10–25 min</span>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            <svg width="22" height="22" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true">
                                <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"></polyline>
                            </svg>
                        </div>
                        <div class="faq-answer" aria-hidden="true">
                            <div class="faq-answer-content">
                                <p>Rapid battery drain usually stems from software or hardware issues. Start with these prioritized checks:</p>
                                <ul>
                                    <li><strong>Power & display:</strong> reduce screen brightness, set sleep timeout, and enable power-saving modes.</li>
                                    <li><strong>Background apps:</strong> check Task Manager / Activity Monitor for processes using CPU, disk or energy — close or uninstall heavy offenders.</li>
                                    <li><strong>Peripherals & radios:</strong> unplug USB devices, disable unused Bluetooth/Wi‑Fi radios when not required.</li>
                                    <li><strong>System updates:</strong> update OS, BIOS/EC, power management and chipset drivers — vendors sometimes fix power bugs.</li>
                                    <li><strong>Battery health:</strong> generate a battery report (<code>powercfg /batteryreport</code> on Windows) and review full-charge vs design capacity and cycle count.</li>
                                </ul>
                                <p><strong>When to replace:</strong> consider a new battery if full-charge capacity is consistently below ~80% of design or if the device dies unexpectedly on battery. Use OEM or reputable replacements.</p>
                                <div class="answer-footer">
                                    <span class="badge">Quick tip</span>
                                    <div class="muted-small">Test in a clean boot or safe mode to rule out 3rd-party apps.</div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <!-- Item 2 -->
                    <div class="faq-item" data-keywords="won't turn on power adapter reset ram bios led beep">
                        <div class="faq-question" role="button" aria-expanded="false" tabindex="0">
                            <div class="q-main">
                                <div class="q-text">How do I fix a laptop that won't turn on?</div>
                                <div class="q-meta">Diagnostics to try before repair</div>
                                <div class="faq-tags"><span class="faq-tag">Difficulty: Medium</span><span class="faq-tag">Time: 15–60 min</span></div>
                            </div>
                            <svg width="22" height="22" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true">
                                <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"></polyline>
                            </svg>
                        </div>
                        <div class="faq-answer" aria-hidden="true">
                            <div class="faq-answer-content">
                                <ol>
                                    <li><strong>Check power source:</strong> test the wall outlet, try a different charger, and inspect the adapter for damage or a faint LED.</li>
                                    <li><strong>Hard reset:</strong> disconnect power, remove removable battery (if present), hold power button 30s, reconnect and retry.</li>
                                    <li><strong>Minimal boot:</strong> disconnect all peripherals, try powering with only essential parts (one RAM stick if applicable).</li>
                                    <li><strong>External display:</strong> attach an external monitor to rule out display failure.</li>
                                    <li><strong>Indicators:</strong> note LED blink/beep patterns and consult vendor docs for error codes.</li>
                                </ol>
                                <p><strong>Safety:</strong> if you detect burning smell, visible damage, or the device still shows no signs of life (no LEDs), stop and get professional help — PSU or motherboard faults can be dangerous.</p>
                                <div class="answer-footer">
                                    <span class="badge">Safety</span>
                                    <div class="muted-small">Avoid probing power circuitry unless you have ESD training and the right tools.</div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <!-- Item 3 -->
                    <div class="faq-item" data-keywords="overheating fan thermal paste cleaning vents cooling pad thermal">
                        <div class="faq-question" role="button" aria-expanded="false" tabindex="0">
                            <div class="q-main">
                                <div class="q-text">What causes laptop overheating and how do I prevent it?</div>
                                <div class="q-meta">Airflow, maintenance, and monitoring</div>
                                <div class="faq-tags"><span class="faq-tag">Difficulty: Easy → Advanced</span><span class="faq-tag">Time: 10–120 min</span></div>
                            </div>
                            <svg width="22" height="22" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true">
                                <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"></polyline>
                            </svg>
                        </div>
                        <div class="faq-answer" aria-hidden="true">
                            <div class="faq-answer-content">
                                <p>Overheating is commonly caused by dust-clogged vents, failing fans, poor thermal interface, or sustained heavy workloads.</p>
                                <ul>
                                    <li><strong>Immediate:</strong> stop heavy tasks, move to a cool surface, let the laptop cool down.</li>
                                    <li><strong>External cleaning:</strong> use short bursts of compressed air on vents; avoid spinning fans faster than they spin normally.</li>
                                    <li><strong>Software control:</strong> reduce power profiles, cap CPU max state, use vendor fan utilities to increase cooling when needed.</li>
                                    <li><strong>Service-level:</strong> if temps remain high, reapply quality thermal paste and replace failing fans or thermal pads (requires disassembly).</li>
                                </ul>
                                <p><strong>Monitor:</strong> use tools like HWInfo (Windows) or Intel Power Gadget (macOS) to log temperatures. If idle temps >60°C or peak >95°C under light workloads, seek service.</p>
                                <div class="answer-footer">
                                    <span class="badge">Monitor</span>
                                    <div class="muted-small">Capture a short log while reproducing the issue to share with a technician.</div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <!-- Item 4 -->
                    <div class="faq-item" data-keywords="slow performance ssd ram malware startup disk">
                        <div class="faq-question" role="button" aria-expanded="false" tabindex="0">
                            <div class="q-main">
                                <div class="q-text">Why is my laptop running so slow?</div>
                                <div class="q-meta">Performance troubleshooting & upgrades</div>
                                <div class="faq-tags"><span class="faq-tag">Difficulty: Easy → Medium</span><span class="faq-tag">Time: 10–90 min</span></div>
                            </div>
                            <svg width="22" height="22" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true">
                                <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"></polyline>
                            </svg>
                        </div>
                        <div class="faq-answer" aria-hidden="true">
                            <div class="faq-answer-content">
                                <ol>
                                    <li><strong>Resource check:</strong> open Task Manager/Activity Monitor and sort by CPU, Memory, Disk to find culprits.</li>
                                    <li><strong>Malware & cleanup:</strong> run a full antivirus scan, remove bloatware, and clear temporary files.</li>
                                    <li><strong>Storage:</strong> HDD → SSD upgrade yields the biggest user-visible improvement.</li>
                                    <li><strong>RAM & drivers:</strong> add RAM if memory is saturated; update chipset/graphics drivers.</li>
                                    <li><strong>Thermals:</strong> ensure cooling is adequate to avoid thermal throttling.</li>
                                </ol>
                                <p><strong>If still slow:</strong> test with a fresh user account or consider a clean OS reinstall after backing up data.</p>
                                <div class="answer-footer">
                                    <span class="badge">Tip</span>
                                    <div class="muted-small">Measure boot time and app launch before/after changes to quantify improvement.</div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <!-- Item 5 -->
                    <div class="faq-item" data-keywords="screen flicker driver refresh-rate cable panel">
                        <div class="faq-question" role="button" aria-expanded="false" tabindex="0">
                            <div class="q-main">
                                <div class="q-text">How do I fix a laptop screen that's flickering?</div>
                                <div class="q-meta">Driver, settings, and hardware checks</div>
                                <div class="faq-tags"><span class="faq-tag">Difficulty: Easy → Advanced</span><span class="faq-tag">Time: 10–60 min</span></div>
                            </div>
                            <svg width="22" height="22" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true">
                                <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"></polyline>
                            </svg>
                        </div>
                        <div class="faq-answer" aria-hidden="true">
                            <div class="faq-answer-content">
                                <ul>
                                    <li>Update display drivers from Intel/NVIDIA/AMD and install any firmware updates.</li>
                                    <li>Check and adjust refresh rate/resolution in Display settings—use recommended values.</li>
                                    <li>Boot into safe mode: if flicker stops, it's likely software/driver related.</li>
                                    <li>If flicker persists, test with an external monitor; if external is fine, suspect panel/cable — professional repair required.</li>
                                </ul>
                                <div class="answer-footer">
                                    <span class="badge">Check</span>
                                    <div class="muted-small">Recording a short video of the flicker helps technicians pinpoint the issue.</div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <!-- Item 6 -->
                    <div class="faq-item" data-keywords="keyboard not working keys device manager drivers liquid">
                        <div class="faq-question" role="button" aria-expanded="false" tabindex="0">
                            <div class="q-main">
                                <div class="q-text">My laptop keyboard isn't working. What should I do?</div>
                                <div class="q-meta">Troubleshooting steps</div>
                                <div class="faq-tags"><span class="faq-tag">Difficulty: Easy → Medium</span><span class="faq-tag">Time: 5–45 min</span></div>
                            </div>
                            <svg width="22" height="22" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true">
                                <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"></polyline>
                            </svg>
                        </div>
                        <div class="faq-answer" aria-hidden="true">
                            <div class="faq-answer-content">
                                <ul>
                                    <li>Restart and test in BIOS/login screen; if keys work there it's likely a driver or OS issue.</li>
                                    <li>Update or reinstall keyboard drivers via Device Manager (Windows).</li>
                                    <li>Try an external USB keyboard to confirm whether the built-in keyboard is faulty.</li>
                                    <li>If sticky keys or liquid damage, power off immediately and arrange professional cleaning/repair to prevent corrosion.</li>
                                </ul>
                                <div class="answer-footer">
                                    <span class="badge">Note</span>
                                    <div class="muted-small">If liquid was spilled, avoid powering on — corrosion spreads if powered.</div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <!-- Item 7 -->
                    <div class="faq-item" data-keywords="cleaning maintenance vents fans internal compressed-air">
                        <div class="faq-question" role="button" aria-expanded="false" tabindex="0">
                            <div class="q-main">
                                <div class="q-text">How often should I clean my laptop?</div>
                                <div class="q-meta">Routine maintenance schedule</div>
                                <div class="faq-tags"><span class="faq-tag">Difficulty: Easy → Advanced</span><span class="faq-tag">Time: 5–60 min</span></div>
                            </div>
                            <svg width="22" height="22" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true">
                                <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"></polyline>
                            </svg>
                        </div>
                        <div class="faq-answer" aria-hidden="true">
                            <div class="faq-answer-content">
                                <p>Recommended cleaning cadence:</p>
                                <ul>
                                    <li><strong>Weekly:</strong> wipe the chassis and keys with a microfiber cloth; keep liquids away.</li>
                                    <li><strong>Every 3–6 months:</strong> use compressed air on vents (external cleaning).</li>
                                    <li><strong>Every 6–12 months:</strong> internal cleaning (open chassis) for heavy-use or dusty environments — have a technician if unsure.</li>
                                </ul>
                                <p>Always power off, unplug, and remove battery (if removable) before cleaning. Use ESD precautions when opening the case.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

